prompt_template:
Create a {ASPECT_RATIO} image in the "Red Yellow Grunge Skate Cover Style" visual style.

Subject: {SUBJECT}
Action: {SUBJECT_ACTION}
Prop/Product: {PRODUCT_OR_PROP}
Location: {LOCATION}
Background: {BACKGROUND_ELEMENTS}
Main text: {MAIN_TEXT}
Secondary text: {SECONDARY_TEXT}
Accent symbol: {ACCENT_SYMBOL}
Wardrobe/styling: {WARDROBE_STYLE}
Style fidelity anchors: {STYLE_FIDELITY_ANCHORS}
Source content to avoid: {SOURCE_CONTENT_TO_AVOID}

Apply these style rules as concrete visual requirements:
- Composition: a loud underground magazine-cover layout with an oversized warped masthead occupying the top third or half of the frame, one large flash-lit photo cutout overlapping the title, a dark tilted photographic setting behind it, and dense boxed callouts clustered near the lower and side edges.
- Typography: main headline lettering is all caps, hand-cut, warped bubble or slab display type with red fill, thick saturated yellow outline, rough ink edges, tight spacing, and slightly uneven baselines; supporting text is stacked uppercase inside chunky red/yellow callout labels.
- Color: dominate the graphic system with hot red and saturated yellow, grounded by black, concrete gray, and cool blue-gray night photography; keep colors screen-printed, contaminated, and slightly misregistered.
- Texture and lighting: use harsh direct flash on the cutout subject, darker ambient background photography, coarse paper grain, scanner noise, halftone dirt, ink spread, soft blur, and worn zine-cover surface.
- Graphic elements: add thick-bordered sticker labels, short editorial blurbs, rough rectangular boxes, compact name-list blocks, and a small accent symbol, all integrated into the crowded cover hierarchy.

Avoid: no skateboarder, no skateboard, no vintage car, no lost skatepark story, no copied source text, no copied names, no copied face or outfit, no real logos, no watermark, no QR code, no platform UI, no clean vector poster, no 3D render, no minimalist layout, no glossy luxury editorial finish, no neat modern typography.

Important content rule: match the reference style first, then change the source content. Use new subjects, new scene details, new props or products, and new text, while preserving the style fidelity anchors.
